00:00:22.250 --> 00:00:27.340
PROFESSOR: So this is
an example in SCET one

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:33.715
where the degrees of freedom
in the p plus p minus plane

00:00:33.715 --> 00:00:34.465
looked as follows.

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:48.470
So we had hard modes
that lived out here at p

00:00:48.470 --> 00:00:52.880
squared in order some
large scale q squared,

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:56.590
then we had collinear
modes for the two jets

00:00:56.590 --> 00:00:58.660
that are going to be
going back to back,

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:00.580
and I'll draw the
picture in a second.

00:01:00.580 --> 00:01:02.530
Then there were some
ultra soft modes

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:05.500
as well that describe
radiation between the jets.

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:09.100
And then there can be also
some lambda QCD modes,

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:11.545
and we'll talk about
them a bit today too.

00:01:11.545 --> 00:01:13.670
So there's a lot of different
things going on here,

00:01:13.670 --> 00:01:16.460
but we'll see that actually
we can understand everything

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:19.210
and organize things using SCET.

00:01:19.210 --> 00:01:22.720
So what's the picture
for these modes?

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:26.350
We have back-to-back jets.

00:01:26.350 --> 00:01:30.655
Let me draw one jet this
way, one jet this way.

00:01:30.655 --> 00:01:31.750
I should use some color.

00:01:39.730 --> 00:01:40.990
So there's one of our jets.

00:01:48.690 --> 00:01:52.800
There's another, and then
there can be soft radiation.

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:00.180
And between these
jets, there can also

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:03.498
be soft radiation
physically within the jets,

00:02:03.498 --> 00:02:05.040
but there's no
directional dependence

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:06.150
to the soft radiation.

00:02:14.390 --> 00:02:18.660
And then set that this is blue.

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:25.384
This and this so far are
orange in my picture.

00:02:25.384 --> 00:02:31.200
This is green, and then
there's some hard interactions,

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:35.590
which we've already
sort of localized

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:37.480
into a dot in this picture.

00:02:42.860 --> 00:02:44.500
So what we're doing
is we're colliding

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:48.130
e plus e minus producing
a virtual photon or z

00:02:48.130 --> 00:02:55.490
and then from that
producing, if you like,

00:02:55.490 --> 00:02:58.100
a state which is full of
collinear modes, state which

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:00.770
is full of the other
type of collinear

00:03:00.770 --> 00:03:04.130
modes and ultra soft particles.

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:09.020
And this is in the
center of mass frame,

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:12.512
or that's kind of how you
could think about it in SCET,

00:03:12.512 --> 00:03:13.970
or physically what
you're producing

00:03:13.970 --> 00:03:24.200
is you're producing jet 1
plus jet 2 plus soft radiation

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:29.165
or ultra soft
hadrons, soft hadrons.

00:03:39.525 --> 00:03:41.650
OK, so the first scale that
you want to think about

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:46.270
is the hard scale,
and so that is just

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:48.820
the q squared to the
virtual photon or z.

00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:51.640
So if you think about
the Feynman diagram,

00:03:51.640 --> 00:03:53.430
there's e plus e minus.

00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:55.660
Here's q mu.

00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:57.310
You're going to have
a pair of quarks

00:03:57.310 --> 00:04:00.358
that that virtual
particle can couple to,

00:04:00.358 --> 00:04:01.900
and there could be
additional gluons.

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:08.320
But the hard scale is set
by the virtual photon or z.

00:04:13.050 --> 00:04:15.750
So there's going to be
some scale associated

00:04:15.750 --> 00:04:18.209
to that hard scale q.

00:04:18.209 --> 00:04:20.529
If you want to think about
it as a normalization scale,

00:04:20.529 --> 00:04:22.029
there'll be some
scale where we want

00:04:22.029 --> 00:04:24.105
to match from QCD
onto SCET, and that's

00:04:24.105 --> 00:04:25.230
going to be the hard scale.

00:04:35.126 --> 00:04:36.940
So I'll call that scale mu h.

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:43.820
So then something physical
has to set these other scales

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:46.790
in the picture,
and the next thing

00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:51.050
that we need to talk about is
what we're going to measure.

00:04:51.050 --> 00:04:53.570
In principle, if you
collide e plus e minus

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:56.150
and you produce hadrons,
you could have lots

00:04:56.150 --> 00:04:57.650
of different possibilities.

00:04:57.650 --> 00:05:00.380
In particular, you could
have not dijets but trijets,

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:03.650
so you could have a third
jet and made it from a gluon.

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:06.560
And some kind of measurement
that we do on the final state

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:09.590
is going to restrict us to this
configuration with just two

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:10.790
jets.

00:05:10.790 --> 00:05:12.830
And the one we'll
talk about to start

00:05:12.830 --> 00:05:16.460
is what's called hemisphere
invariant masses, which

00:05:16.460 --> 00:05:17.670
we already mentioned earlier.

00:05:21.598 --> 00:05:23.390
So the way that you
should think about this

00:05:23.390 --> 00:05:27.680
is you take all the
final state particles,

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:30.320
and you could just take the
sum of all their momenta

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:36.970
and divide it into two parts,
those that are in hemisphere A

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:40.410
and those that are
in hemisphere B.

00:05:40.410 --> 00:05:47.960
So let me augment my
figure here by saying

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:51.718
that there's two hemispheres.

00:05:51.718 --> 00:05:53.760
And then what these masses
are, which I'll call m

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:57.350
squared and then
bar squared are just

00:05:57.350 --> 00:06:02.580
the four vectors squared for
p, for the a, and the b guy.

00:06:02.580 --> 00:06:06.660
So written in terms of
the individual particles

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:10.200
in that hemisphere, you
sum up all their four

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:13.920
vectors for the particles in
that hemisphere and square it,

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:30.050
and then likewise for B.

00:06:30.050 --> 00:06:33.170
And if you're measuring
these two things,

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:35.060
we talked about earlier
the fact that you

00:06:35.060 --> 00:06:37.250
could specify that it
was a jet by demanding

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:38.730
that they're small.

00:06:38.730 --> 00:06:45.990
So the dijets is
going to be m squared

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:49.908
and then bar squared
much less than q squared.

00:06:49.908 --> 00:06:52.200
And if you had trijets, you
wouldn't-- that wouldn't be

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:54.030
the case because
if you had trijets,

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:58.760
you'd have two particle-- two
jets in this hemisphere at wide

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:01.520
angles, and those-- that wide
angle would produce a large q

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:05.350
squared, a large and
variant mass of m squared.

00:07:05.350 --> 00:07:06.830
That's of order q squared.

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:08.770
But if you just
have a single jet,

00:07:08.770 --> 00:07:10.970
then you can have
a small m squared,

00:07:10.970 --> 00:07:13.735
so the small m squared limit is
what forces you to have dijets.

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:20.160
And these guys here,
it also puts us

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.850
in the kinematic situation
where we have our n collinear

00:07:23.850 --> 00:07:27.330
modes for one jet and
n bar collinear modes

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:29.953
for the other jet.

00:07:29.953 --> 00:07:32.370
So those are two of the degrees
of freedom in our picture.

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:40.660
So I'm reminding you of some
things we talked about before,

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:44.280
but it was a while ago so--

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:47.857
and the power counting
parameter here is m over q.

00:07:47.857 --> 00:07:49.440
And so if you want
to say that there's

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:52.470
a scale in this picture
associated to the collinear

00:07:52.470 --> 00:07:57.000
modes, then you would say
it's on a kind of jet scale,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:58.394
and that's of order m.

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:08.860
OK, any questions so far?

00:08:08.860 --> 00:08:17.360
So then there's the
ultra soft radiation,

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:19.900
which is being ultra
soft, it's uniform.

00:08:19.900 --> 00:08:22.221
It's not collimated
in any direction.

00:08:25.562 --> 00:08:27.520
It's the thing that gives
you the communication

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:28.360
between the jets.

00:08:32.919 --> 00:08:35.710
The jets are going to decouple
from each other in the sense

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:38.539
that interactions directly
between the n collinear and n

00:08:38.539 --> 00:08:42.270
bar collinear modes is all
going into the pink dot,

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:45.280
but there can be long distance
communication between the jets

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:47.170
caused by the ultra soft modes.

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:53.410
So, really, what I mean here
is long distance communication.

00:08:53.410 --> 00:08:55.810
Short distance communication
can happen too.

00:08:55.810 --> 00:08:59.350
That's what the pink dot is, but
that's, in some sense, simpler.

00:08:59.350 --> 00:09:00.940
Long distance
communication can only

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:04.630
happen by this ultra
soft radiation.

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:08.500
And we know about how
ultra soft radiation

00:09:08.500 --> 00:09:10.180
interacts with
energetic particles,

00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:13.060
and in particular, what we
know is that it's eikonal.

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:16.000
That came out of our
Lagrangian description

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.520
of ultra soft radiation.

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:22.340
And that will have
implications here.

00:09:22.340 --> 00:09:23.950
So what is this
ultra soft radiation?

00:09:23.950 --> 00:09:26.182
It's radiation that
has energy that's

00:09:26.182 --> 00:09:27.265
of order q lambda squared.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:36.010
And so that's m squared
over q energy radiation,

00:09:36.010 --> 00:09:39.370
and so the soft scale,
which is the next scale down

00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:44.890
in the picture, ultra soft
scale, is m squared over q.

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:47.590
Often, people will--
because there's

00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:51.760
no soft radiation in this
setup, sometimes people

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:54.250
will just drop the ultra
and just call it soft.

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:56.760
That's very common.

00:09:56.760 --> 00:09:58.810
I'll try to always
call it ultra soft here

00:09:58.810 --> 00:10:01.750
because we'll be drawing
some distinctions with SCET 2

00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:04.810
examples, and in those examples,
we have soft and collinear.

00:10:04.810 --> 00:10:07.120
In this example, we have
ultra soft and collinear,

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:09.520
so I'll keep trying
to call it ultra soft.

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:11.050
But you can see
that I've already

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:12.910
abbreviated it to
u soft to make it

00:10:12.910 --> 00:10:15.280
look more and more like soft.

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:17.200
Anyway, but in the
literature, people

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:20.470
often just drop the u
completely and call it soft.

00:10:20.470 --> 00:10:23.520
Something to be aware of.

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:27.550
OK, so this actually--
this radiation here,

00:10:27.550 --> 00:10:30.040
this is kind of the
largest scale that

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:32.930
can show up in
the soft function,

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:34.450
and there's also lambda QCD.

00:10:39.310 --> 00:10:41.470
And that's a scale
that, at least to start,

00:10:41.470 --> 00:10:43.220
we're going to leave
in the soft function.

00:10:51.148 --> 00:10:53.190
So if we go back to our
picture over here, that's

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:57.870
why I put both the ultra soft
mode side up on this hyperbola

00:10:57.870 --> 00:11:03.210
there, which is this m
squared over q line, mu over m

00:11:03.210 --> 00:11:04.800
squared over q line.

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:06.810
That's why I made it
orange, and I also

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:10.320
made orange this lambda QCD
because they're together.

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:12.480
And you can think of
it as just that there's

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:16.320
some modes that are capturing
this entire region, which

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:18.930
are the ultra soft modes.

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:20.430
Now there are two--

00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:25.500
if m squared over q was
of order lambda QCD, then

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:26.570
those are the same thing.

00:11:26.570 --> 00:11:29.190
So there's kind of two
possibilities here.

00:11:29.190 --> 00:11:35.250
You could have m squared
over q of order lambda QCD,

00:11:35.250 --> 00:11:39.466
and that means that this
scale is not non-perturbative.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:45.180
And this is what's
called, for reasons

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:50.137
that will become apparent by the
end of lecture, the peak region

00:11:50.137 --> 00:11:52.470
because this is actually the
region of the cross section

00:11:52.470 --> 00:11:53.952
where there's a peak.

00:11:53.952 --> 00:11:56.890
OK, that's why it's
called the peak region.

00:11:56.890 --> 00:12:01.290
And in this region, you have
the following hierarchy.

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:05.110
You have mu h is much
greater than mu j.

00:12:05.110 --> 00:12:07.920
Mu j is much greater
than mu s, but mu

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:10.350
s is of order lambda QCD.

00:12:10.350 --> 00:12:15.590
OK, so if we take this
to always be true,

00:12:15.590 --> 00:12:18.020
then we're in this situation.

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:19.860
And there is
another possibility,

00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:23.510
and that is that there's
really a separation

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:27.530
between these hyperbolas that's
just as large or hierarchical

00:12:27.530 --> 00:12:30.030
as the previous separations.

00:12:30.030 --> 00:12:34.130
So if this thing is much
bigger than lambda QCD,

00:12:34.130 --> 00:12:37.370
that's another
possibility, and there'll

00:12:37.370 --> 00:12:39.260
be a region of phase
based where this is true

00:12:39.260 --> 00:12:42.090
and a region of phase
based where this is true.

00:12:42.090 --> 00:12:43.340
The second one is--

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:46.430
here, the soft, there's--

00:12:49.990 --> 00:12:59.500
here there is perturbative
ultra soft radiation,

00:12:59.500 --> 00:13:01.960
so you can just calculate
it order by order

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:05.860
in the ultra soft scale,
which is this scale, which

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:09.910
is perturbative because it's
much bigger than lambda QCD.

00:13:09.910 --> 00:13:11.740
And this is what's
called the tail region.

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:19.030
And the analog of
this statement here

00:13:19.030 --> 00:13:21.835
is that we have a hierarchy
between everybody.

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:36.840
So when we do this analysis,
what we're going to do

00:13:36.840 --> 00:13:39.190
is we're going to do
a power expansion.

00:13:39.190 --> 00:13:41.580
And you can say, well,
the power expansion

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:43.600
is just what you told
me, m squared over--

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:45.060
m squared much less
than q squared,

00:13:45.060 --> 00:13:47.700
but you also have to worry
about this when you're

00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:50.320
doing the power expansion.

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:52.710
So one way of thinking
about it is just exactly

00:13:52.710 --> 00:13:56.490
as I'm writing here, and
that's how I want to advocate.

00:13:56.490 --> 00:13:59.683
The things you're expanding
in are these assumptions.

00:13:59.683 --> 00:14:01.350
And you can see that
in these two cases,

00:14:01.350 --> 00:14:03.000
there's a slightly
different set up.

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:20.110
So usually, when you
have an effective theory,

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:23.860
you have to define this from
the beginning because the way

00:14:23.860 --> 00:14:27.340
you proceed and how you
set up your theory is going

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:30.010
to depend on whether
you're in this situation

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:32.260
or this situation.

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:35.560
But part of this story is the
same in these two situations,

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:38.000
namely the first two greater
thans, much greater thans

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:39.470
are the same.

00:14:39.470 --> 00:14:41.830
And so that, we can proceed
without worrying about this.

00:14:45.372 --> 00:14:47.330
And then we can make this
distinction later on,

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:49.038
and that's what my
picture was advocating

00:14:49.038 --> 00:14:56.167
for by having these guys
in the same category.

00:14:56.167 --> 00:14:57.250
So hopefully that's clear.

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:17.590
OK, so if you're
in the tail region,

00:15:17.590 --> 00:15:24.310
there's going to be
power corrections,

00:15:24.310 --> 00:15:28.120
and these are actually the most
important power corrections

00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:35.350
that come as powers of lambda
QCD over the soft scale

00:15:35.350 --> 00:15:36.040
to some power.

00:15:36.040 --> 00:15:42.220
But you're going to have
a power expansion in that.

00:15:42.220 --> 00:15:46.000
So that's the-- if you
like in this situation

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:47.500
when you're in the
tail region, you

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:50.710
can have power corrections that
are non-perturbative by having

00:15:50.710 --> 00:15:52.330
ratios of these
things, lambda QCD

00:15:52.330 --> 00:15:55.340
over this over that over this.

00:15:55.340 --> 00:15:58.966
But the biggest one are these
guys over the soft scale,

00:15:58.966 --> 00:16:00.700
so that's the next
smallest scale.

00:16:05.618 --> 00:16:07.410
But if you neglect
these, the leading order

00:16:07.410 --> 00:16:09.750
cross section in this
region is perturbative.

00:16:19.580 --> 00:16:25.460
Now you know you can have any
power here, and those exist.

00:16:25.460 --> 00:16:28.100
What happens in
the peak region is

00:16:28.100 --> 00:16:31.490
that thinking about those as
an expansion is no longer good.

00:16:38.120 --> 00:16:41.960
And you have to take all
of them and treat them

00:16:41.960 --> 00:16:47.930
as if they're order
one and for any k,

00:16:47.930 --> 00:16:50.368
and that ends up
meaning that there's

00:16:50.368 --> 00:16:52.160
going to be some
non-perturbative function,

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:54.160
like a Parton distribution
function in the sense

00:16:54.160 --> 00:16:58.490
that it's non-perturbative,
that describes part of what's

00:16:58.490 --> 00:17:04.800
going on here in this region.

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:06.740
And that, we just see
from our power counting,

00:17:06.740 --> 00:17:08.365
and our power counting
already tells us

00:17:08.365 --> 00:17:11.677
that that's what's
going to happen.

00:17:11.677 --> 00:17:13.260
So we can learn a
lot just by thinking

00:17:13.260 --> 00:17:16.030
about the scales and the problem
and thinking about the power

00:17:16.030 --> 00:17:16.530
counting.

00:17:25.970 --> 00:17:32.463
So you could ask about
other power corrections.

00:17:36.170 --> 00:17:37.730
So there's a set of
power connections

00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:41.660
where you would expand
