perp momentum there either.

00:36:30.190 --> 00:36:33.550
So that guy is really just--

00:36:33.550 --> 00:36:45.620
we can pull out a pn minus and
then we have pn plus k sa plus.

00:36:45.620 --> 00:36:49.970
And we also know
that pn minus is q.

00:36:49.970 --> 00:36:52.100
That was fixed by kinematics.

00:36:52.100 --> 00:36:54.640
OK, so this simplifies
quite a bit.

00:36:57.340 --> 00:36:59.840
And we're going to drop all the
powers of [INAUDIBLE] terms.

00:37:17.620 --> 00:37:21.770
All right, so that is one thing.

00:37:21.770 --> 00:37:28.660
So then I can do what I said
in words, write this guy,

00:37:28.660 --> 00:37:34.930
and it will have
these two deltas that

00:37:34.930 --> 00:37:37.850
are under similar acts.

00:37:37.850 --> 00:37:40.210
They don't commute through
with it-- without it.

00:37:40.210 --> 00:37:43.010
They depend on x.

00:37:43.010 --> 00:37:46.210
Now another thing
we would like to do

00:37:46.210 --> 00:37:50.560
is the factorize
the measurement.

00:37:50.560 --> 00:37:52.090
So this measurement
here involves

00:37:52.090 --> 00:37:55.630
the sum of a plus momentum
collinear and a plus momentum

00:37:55.630 --> 00:37:57.340
in soft.

00:37:57.340 --> 00:37:58.810
And it's all in
one delta function.

00:37:58.810 --> 00:38:00.852
We'd like to write it as
separate delta functions

00:38:00.852 --> 00:38:03.760
that we can associate with
those different parts here,

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:07.150
one delta-- we'd like to
have a separate thing here

00:38:07.150 --> 00:38:08.560
from these guys.

00:38:08.560 --> 00:38:10.880
And that's actually
very easy to do.

00:38:10.880 --> 00:38:16.596
We simply write the following.

00:38:27.530 --> 00:38:29.632
Just introduce some
more delta functions.

00:38:38.800 --> 00:38:42.270
So there's this tying
together delta function.

00:38:42.270 --> 00:38:45.960
K plus is just some
dummy variable.

00:38:45.960 --> 00:38:47.580
It's not the momentum
of any state.

00:38:47.580 --> 00:38:54.340
It's just a dummy variable,
whereas pn plus and ksa plus

00:38:54.340 --> 00:38:57.560
were momenta of
particles in the state.

00:38:57.560 --> 00:39:01.340
So this guy can then
associate with the--

00:39:01.340 --> 00:39:11.100
put them together with the
n collinear matrix element,

00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:12.150
which is this guy here.

00:39:15.454 --> 00:39:17.040
I forget what color he was.

00:39:21.990 --> 00:39:27.360
And then for the
ultra soft, we can

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:29.730
associated this delta function.

00:39:32.123 --> 00:39:33.540
So that's what I
mean by factoring

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:35.332
the measurement, that
we can put the piece,

00:39:35.332 --> 00:39:36.990
depended on the state, together.

00:39:36.990 --> 00:39:39.810
And then you can see
that we can move our--

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:42.660
well, OK, we have to also
factor this delta function.

00:39:42.660 --> 00:39:45.360
I should say that too.

00:39:45.360 --> 00:39:48.760
That's the part that I'm
not going to go through,

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:53.100
but we can play similar
games expanding and factoring

00:39:53.100 --> 00:39:56.250
this delta four as well.

00:39:56.250 --> 00:39:59.730
And that's besides just
being a little bit tedious,

00:39:59.730 --> 00:40:04.970
it's not really any
more difficult. Maybe

00:40:04.970 --> 00:40:07.440
a little more difficult.

00:40:07.440 --> 00:40:08.660
So we factor that guy too.

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:17.900
And then there's one other
trick that we want to do,

00:40:17.900 --> 00:40:23.320
which is useful, and
that is that we can write

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:24.910
some deltas in Fourier's space.

00:40:37.135 --> 00:40:38.760
So we can always
write a delta function

00:40:38.760 --> 00:40:42.750
as an integral over a
phase, and that's convenient

00:40:42.750 --> 00:40:44.677
because in the phase,
the momenta that

00:40:44.677 --> 00:40:46.260
are in the delta
function also factor.

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:52.870
So I can write it as a product
of two separate factors

00:40:52.870 --> 00:40:53.410
like this.

00:40:56.002 --> 00:40:58.150
There's some halves.

00:40:58.150 --> 00:41:01.060
It's conventional.

00:41:01.060 --> 00:41:05.230
OK, so this guy here,
which is the guy that

00:41:05.230 --> 00:41:07.150
is associated to
the state, it looks

00:41:07.150 --> 00:41:09.250
like a translation operator.

00:41:09.250 --> 00:41:13.960
if you have an e to the i
x dot p, that you can use.

00:41:13.960 --> 00:41:16.030
You can put into
your matrix element,

00:41:16.030 --> 00:41:19.000
and you can translate
the fields, which

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.802
are in this formula all at 0.

00:41:21.802 --> 00:41:25.000
They're all at space time 0.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.370
What you can do
with this guy here

00:41:27.370 --> 00:41:31.300
is you can put it into
the matrix element

00:41:31.300 --> 00:41:33.790
and translate the
fields to point x.

00:41:45.037 --> 00:41:49.240
And then you'd have
a chi and x minus.

00:41:49.240 --> 00:41:51.910
So that's how we can
deal with that guy.

00:41:51.910 --> 00:41:55.570
And so if we do a bunch
of stuff like that I'm not

00:41:55.570 --> 00:41:58.870
going to go through on the
board for you, after some work,

00:41:58.870 --> 00:42:02.200
we get something just kind
of an intermediate step

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:10.260
of our factorization,
which I'll write out

00:42:10.260 --> 00:42:13.320
so you can get some idea of--

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:16.140
if I jump to the final answer,
it's kind of too simple

00:42:16.140 --> 00:42:18.850
to see what's going on.

00:42:18.850 --> 00:42:20.460
So let's write this one out.

00:42:32.360 --> 00:42:36.423
So I was focusing on the n
collinear matrix element,

00:42:36.423 --> 00:42:38.840
and everything I was writing,
I wrote this delta function.

00:42:38.840 --> 00:42:41.540
But there's, of course, another
one for the delta n bar,

00:42:41.540 --> 00:42:43.850
and I do the same thing for him.

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:46.740
So we got k plus and l plus
by factoring the measurement

00:42:46.740 --> 00:42:47.240
there.

00:42:47.240 --> 00:42:49.310
You get a k minus and
an l minus by factoring

00:42:49.310 --> 00:42:50.495
the other measurement.

00:43:02.880 --> 00:43:05.880
One thing that comes into--

00:43:05.880 --> 00:43:08.060
that makes this guy here
a little more complicated

00:43:08.060 --> 00:43:10.477
is you have to think a little
bit about residual and label

00:43:10.477 --> 00:43:11.420
momentum.

00:43:11.420 --> 00:43:16.640
But at the end of the day, the
result is what I'm writing.

00:43:36.230 --> 00:43:43.640
So this is going to be
completely factorizing to three

00:43:43.640 --> 00:43:44.495
independent things.

00:44:02.570 --> 00:44:05.900
There's one set of collinear
fields for the quark,

00:44:05.900 --> 00:44:09.830
and there's another for
the antiquark if you like.

00:44:09.830 --> 00:44:11.480
You're specifying
whether it's a quark

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:13.290
or an antiquark with a label.

00:44:13.290 --> 00:44:16.350
So the fact that this
label here is positive

00:44:16.350 --> 00:44:20.298
means that this is a quark, and
maybe this should be a minus q.

00:44:26.860 --> 00:44:31.538
And then this guy is
specifying the antiquark,

00:44:31.538 --> 00:44:32.830
and then there's the soft part.

00:45:04.660 --> 00:45:10.760
OK, so this is a fairly
messy one board expression,

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:14.140
but this guy here is factored.

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:16.570
We have the hard modes
here, collinear modes,

00:45:16.570 --> 00:45:19.450
n collinear here, and
bar collinear there,

00:45:19.450 --> 00:45:26.920
and the ultra soft goes
here, which I've already

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:30.100
dropped in my ultra soft.

00:45:30.100 --> 00:45:35.020
So this last guy if you think
about what this matrix element

00:45:35.020 --> 00:45:39.090
is it's just some function.

00:45:39.090 --> 00:45:40.268
We sum over all x of this.

00:45:40.268 --> 00:45:42.060
So we sum over all the
intermediate states.

00:45:42.060 --> 00:45:44.185
The only thing we're fixing
are l plus and l minus.

00:45:48.555 --> 00:45:50.180
So when we sum over
states, we actually

00:45:50.180 --> 00:45:52.990
integrate the momentum
of particles in the state

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:54.090
if you can think of that.

00:45:54.090 --> 00:45:55.010
Those are different states.

00:45:55.010 --> 00:45:57.427
You have to sum over them too,
but it's a continuous label

00:45:57.427 --> 00:46:01.467
and therefore you integrate
over the phase base.

00:46:01.467 --> 00:46:03.800
And that's what we mean when
we write the sum over axis.

00:46:03.800 --> 00:46:06.025
That includes phase
based intervals.

00:46:08.940 --> 00:46:10.890
And so the only--
so this momentum

00:46:10.890 --> 00:46:12.990
gets integrated
over if you like,

00:46:12.990 --> 00:46:15.570
but then it gets--
there's a component that

00:46:15.570 --> 00:46:18.960
gets fixed, which is the total
momentum of plus or minus

00:46:18.960 --> 00:46:21.055
momentum in each hemisphere.

00:46:21.055 --> 00:46:22.305
So this is just some function.

00:46:29.900 --> 00:46:34.880
So that we color the same.

00:46:34.880 --> 00:46:41.367
It's just some function
of l plus or l minus,

00:46:41.367 --> 00:46:42.700
and it's called a soft function.

00:46:49.210 --> 00:46:51.220
And at this stage
of the game, it's

00:46:51.220 --> 00:46:53.905
actually encoding two
different momentum scales.

00:46:57.560 --> 00:47:01.600
The l plus and minus
as well as sort

00:47:01.600 --> 00:47:03.790
of lambda QCD, which I
didn't write explicitly

00:47:03.790 --> 00:47:04.420
as an argument.

00:47:07.060 --> 00:47:11.230
And l plus and
minus, well, we'll

00:47:11.230 --> 00:47:14.260
see later, but you can
think of l plus and minus

00:47:14.260 --> 00:47:19.210
roughly as encoding the scale
that's m squared over q.

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:22.180
This will become more
clear in a minute.

00:47:26.510 --> 00:47:30.181
So again, we need to figure
out what these guys here are.

00:47:30.181 --> 00:47:32.830
That's a little bit more
work but not too much.

00:47:37.550 --> 00:47:41.270
And they're both, of course,
mirrors of each other.

00:47:41.270 --> 00:47:44.560
So really, we just have to be
one of them, and if you like,

00:47:44.560 --> 00:47:47.238
the other is just kind
of charge congregation.

00:47:56.510 --> 00:47:59.170
So this guy here, we're going
to write in Fourier's space.

00:48:01.870 --> 00:48:09.530
That's a convenient
thing to do because what

00:48:09.530 --> 00:48:11.870
we know about the Feynman
rules in Fourier's space

00:48:11.870 --> 00:48:13.580
when we thought about
the Feynman rules

00:48:13.580 --> 00:48:17.690
in Fourier's space, we knew that
the collinear propagators would

00:48:17.690 --> 00:48:20.520
only depend on the
small plus momentum.

00:48:20.520 --> 00:48:23.270
So the x-coordinates
here, the x-coordinates

00:48:23.270 --> 00:48:25.840
of our fields,
those corresponded

00:48:25.840 --> 00:48:30.020
to residual momenta, but
when we do Feynman diagrams,

00:48:30.020 --> 00:48:32.720
there's only the plus
momentum showing up.

00:48:32.720 --> 00:48:34.250
That's the multipole expansion.

00:48:39.248 --> 00:48:41.540
So you could think about it
from the [? phonographs, ?]

00:48:41.540 --> 00:48:44.060
but it's really a
general property

00:48:44.060 --> 00:48:45.490
from the multipole expansion.

00:48:50.550 --> 00:48:54.260
So that means that some of these
integrals here are just trivial

00:48:54.260 --> 00:48:55.550
and give me a delta function.

00:48:59.805 --> 00:49:02.180
So I'm getting delta functions
in some directions because

00:49:02.180 --> 00:49:05.015
of the multipole
expansion in this formula.

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:14.460
Because I aligned
the axis, there

00:49:14.460 --> 00:49:17.210
was no perpendicular momentum,
so it's really just this r plus

00:49:17.210 --> 00:49:19.710
that we get, and this thing
here is called the jet function.

00:49:24.602 --> 00:49:26.810
So this is the non-trivial
function that can show up.

00:49:31.190 --> 00:49:32.300
We do the same thing.

00:49:35.190 --> 00:49:38.480
We do the same thing for the
case with the sum over xn bar,

00:49:38.480 --> 00:49:42.530
and it gives us
another jet function.

00:49:42.530 --> 00:49:47.390
And by charge conjugation,
it's the same jet function.

00:49:47.390 --> 00:49:53.200
But in this case, it would
be q of sum r prime minus

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:55.880
and some other momentum.

00:49:55.880 --> 00:49:58.760
And so what we then do
is we take this formula,

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:03.560
plug it back into here, do all
the integrals, and at the end

00:50:03.560 --> 00:50:05.330
of the day, we can actually do--

00:50:05.330 --> 00:50:08.000
we have lots of delta functions
and lots of integrals.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:10.770
And we can boil everything
down to just two integrals left

00:50:10.770 --> 00:50:11.270
over.

00:50:16.230 --> 00:50:21.810
And that gives us our final
result. So I'll write this way.

00:50:39.710 --> 00:50:42.800
So it boils down
to just involving

00:50:42.800 --> 00:50:44.845
these jet functions
and the soft function,

00:50:44.845 --> 00:50:46.220
and then there's
something that's

00:50:46.220 --> 00:50:50.330
called the hard function, which
is just our Wilson coefficient

00:50:50.330 --> 00:50:50.985
squared.

00:50:50.985 --> 00:50:52.610
So rather than write
Wilson coefficient

00:50:52.610 --> 00:50:56.300
squared all the time, we just
call it another function h.

00:50:56.300 --> 00:50:59.430
So this is the
factorization theorem.

00:50:59.430 --> 00:51:01.790
So you see in this case,
the hard function was just

00:51:01.790 --> 00:51:04.520
a multiplicative
factor unlike dis,

00:51:04.520 --> 00:51:07.653
and what was-- where things
are talking to each other.

00:51:07.653 --> 00:51:09.320
Again, things are
talking to each other,

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:10.760
but it's the soft modes--

00:51:10.760 --> 00:51:13.370
ultra soft modes that
are talking to the jets.

00:51:13.370 --> 00:51:16.250
And ultra soft momenta
can change the mass,

00:51:16.250 --> 00:51:19.460
and that's what kind
of the correct mass--

00:51:19.460 --> 00:51:20.900
this is the total mass.

00:51:20.900 --> 00:51:23.840
The correct mass for the jet
function is the collinear mass,

00:51:23.840 --> 00:51:25.637
and that's this thing
minus this thing.

00:51:25.637 --> 00:51:28.220
So if you wanted to guess this
formula, this is how you do it.

00:51:28.220 --> 00:51:30.800
You'd say m squared, just
from the kinematic relation,

00:51:30.800 --> 00:51:34.212
m squared had a collinear
piece and a soft piece.

00:51:34.212 --> 00:51:36.170
The right thing to evaluate
the jet function at

00:51:36.170 --> 00:51:40.050
would be just the collinear,
so that's the difference.

00:51:40.050 --> 00:51:43.340
And then the soft function
could depend on these momentum,

00:51:43.340 --> 00:51:46.580
and you're basically led
to a formula like this one.

00:51:46.580 --> 00:51:48.560
But we can also just,
with the field theory,

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:50.060
go through and
derive it, and that's

00:51:50.060 --> 00:51:53.600
what I'm convincing you of even
if I was skipping some steps.

00:51:56.860 --> 00:51:59.200
All right, so this is the
dijet factorization theorem

00:51:59.200 --> 00:52:01.855
for hemisphere invariant masses.

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:08.920
And a lot of event
shapes kind of

00:52:08.920 --> 00:52:11.555
go along the pattern
that we've done here.

00:52:11.555 --> 00:52:13.930
If you think about what would
be the difference if I pick

00:52:13.930 --> 00:52:16.870
some other observable both
sides of these masses,

00:52:16.870 --> 00:52:19.930
pick some other thing that you
could measure that would tell

00:52:19.930 --> 00:52:23.350
you that there's dijets, we just
swap out the measurement part,

00:52:23.350 --> 00:52:26.470
and that would lead to-- and
just see where it leads us.

00:52:26.470 --> 00:52:30.068
A lot of the steps would
be exactly the same steps.

00:52:30.068 --> 00:52:31.860
So we did it for one
particular observable,

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:35.260
but steps are the
same if you do others.

00:52:39.820 --> 00:52:41.980
If you're in this situation
where you have dijets,

00:52:41.980 --> 00:52:44.740
there's more than one
way of measuring an event

00:52:44.740 --> 00:52:46.300
to ensure you have dijets.

00:52:46.300 --> 00:52:52.780
There's something called
dijet event shapes.

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:54.740
They go under the names
of things like thrust,

00:52:54.740 --> 00:52:57.460
C parameter, heavy jet mass.

00:53:00.580 --> 00:53:03.423
All these things actually
have factorization theorems

00:53:03.423 --> 00:53:05.590
that you could derive in a
similar way to what we're

00:53:05.590 --> 00:53:06.100
doing here.

