j j integrated

01:07:47.270 --> 01:07:50.390
over so fixing kind
some of the momentum

01:07:50.390 --> 01:07:53.111
and integrating
over the difference.

01:07:53.111 --> 01:07:55.220
So this guy depends
on one momentum,

01:07:55.220 --> 01:07:59.690
and this guy-- these guys depend
on 2, and there's one integral.

01:07:59.690 --> 01:08:03.560
And then s tau is
like one integral

01:08:03.560 --> 01:08:08.240
of kind of something like this.

01:08:08.240 --> 01:08:09.940
So let's call the
integral l prime.

01:08:09.940 --> 01:08:15.420
It's kind of like that.

01:08:19.270 --> 01:08:21.271
So that's what I mean by
asymmetric projection.

01:08:21.271 --> 01:08:22.979
AUDIENCE: And so how
do you know that tau

01:08:22.979 --> 01:08:26.410
can be written as
a function n bar,

01:08:26.410 --> 01:08:30.220
or could another kinematic
variable [INAUDIBLE]??

01:08:30.220 --> 01:08:32.800
PROFESSOR: No, it can be
