01:08:32.800 --> 01:08:35.859
Yeah, because you're still--
if you're in subleading power,

01:08:35.859 --> 01:08:37.865
as long as you're in the
dijet's configuration,

01:08:37.865 --> 01:08:39.490
we've got the right
degrees of freedom.

01:08:39.490 --> 01:08:41.670
We don't need another
jet degree of freedom.

01:08:44.300 --> 01:08:46.090
So if you want to describe--

01:08:46.090 --> 01:08:48.970
you could think about
the thrust distribution.

01:08:48.970 --> 01:08:51.490
Well, let me answer your
question in more detail.

01:08:51.490 --> 01:08:52.990
Let me tell you
where you would have

01:08:52.990 --> 01:08:55.870
to worry about more
degrees of freedom,

01:08:55.870 --> 01:08:59.000
but let me do it in a second.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:16.660
I'll give you-- all right,
so in the thrust case

01:09:16.660 --> 01:09:18.760
and what we said about
masses carries over

01:09:18.760 --> 01:09:24.830
to a formula like this,
where this mu h squared

01:09:24.830 --> 01:09:30.580
being much bigger than
mu j squared, much bigger

01:09:30.580 --> 01:09:31.899
than mu s squared.

01:09:31.899 --> 01:09:39.790
And then that could be much
greater than or of order lambda

01:09:39.790 --> 01:09:41.050
QCD squared.

01:09:41.050 --> 01:09:45.100
And the type of terms that our
factorization theorem would

01:09:45.100 --> 01:09:49.300
be able to resum if we did the
renormalization group evolution

01:09:49.300 --> 01:09:54.340
would be sums of powers
of alpha and logs of tau.

01:09:54.340 --> 01:09:57.490
Tau is dimensionless
variable, and so the kind

01:09:57.490 --> 01:10:00.370
of terms that would show
up in the cross section

01:10:00.370 --> 01:10:05.245
are terms like that plus
non-perturbative effects.

01:10:08.980 --> 01:10:11.700
So if you want to think
the base level, what

01:10:11.700 --> 01:10:15.300
is inside our formula,
it's all these terms.

01:10:15.300 --> 01:10:18.000
We're able to determine them
from our factorization theorem,

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:20.334
and then there's also
some non-perturbative,

01:10:20.334 --> 01:10:23.730
which would be kind of-- and
non-perturbative effects that

01:10:23.730 --> 01:10:26.388
in this f function.

01:10:26.388 --> 01:10:28.380
And the factorization
theorem is telling us

01:10:28.380 --> 01:10:32.350
how to compute these
things and include them.

01:10:32.350 --> 01:10:35.367
So what does it look
like as a picture?

01:10:35.367 --> 01:10:36.950
What does the
cross-section look like?

01:10:39.630 --> 01:10:48.600
So there's a peak as I
promised, and there's kind of--

01:10:48.600 --> 01:10:49.650
and then there's a tail.

01:10:54.030 --> 01:10:59.670
And so this is tau.

01:10:59.670 --> 01:11:02.670
This is d sigma d tau.

01:11:02.670 --> 01:11:06.083
You can always normalize.

01:11:06.083 --> 01:11:07.500
This peak is
happening in the kind

01:11:07.500 --> 01:11:08.670
of non-perturbative region.

01:11:08.670 --> 01:11:14.225
So because it's a
symmetric projection,

01:11:14.225 --> 01:11:15.600
there's a factor
of two, but it's

01:11:15.600 --> 01:11:18.510
kind of basically happening
when taus of order lambda

01:11:18.510 --> 01:11:19.440
QCD over q.

01:11:19.440 --> 01:11:22.630
And we could figure out
that just by power counting.

01:11:22.630 --> 01:11:26.520
And then depending
on the value of cue,

01:11:26.520 --> 01:11:31.050
that sort of for a
typical configuration, tau

01:11:31.050 --> 01:11:32.520
equals 0.1 would
be over somewhere

01:11:32.520 --> 01:11:36.210
over there, et cetera.

01:11:36.210 --> 01:11:39.650
So this is the peak, aptly named
because it looks like a peak.

01:11:39.650 --> 01:11:44.120
And in this peak, there's
non-perturbative effects

01:11:44.120 --> 01:11:46.820
that come from the f.

01:11:46.820 --> 01:11:49.270
This is the tail.

01:11:49.270 --> 01:11:53.270
It could be called
the shoulder, but it's

01:11:53.270 --> 01:11:56.180
kind of once you're
out here and down here,

01:11:56.180 --> 01:11:58.280
this is what you
call the tail where

01:11:58.280 --> 01:12:01.670
you have a perturbative s tau.

01:12:01.670 --> 01:12:07.880
And then you would include
power corrections by expanding.

01:12:07.880 --> 01:12:11.280
And the expansion would give you
lambda QCD over the soft scale,

01:12:11.280 --> 01:12:13.385
which is q tau.

01:12:13.385 --> 01:12:19.430
So this is-- that's that
expansion that we talked about,

01:12:19.430 --> 01:12:22.864
and that comes
from expanding it,

01:12:22.864 --> 01:12:28.862
f, or an expansion
that involves f.

01:12:28.862 --> 01:12:30.530
It's not expanding f.

01:12:34.460 --> 01:12:35.960
Basically, what
these numerators are

01:12:35.960 --> 01:12:39.830
are moments of f once
you do the expansion.

01:12:39.830 --> 01:12:41.930
And then there's
a region out here,

01:12:41.930 --> 01:12:45.110
and in both of these
regions, you have dijets.

01:12:45.110 --> 01:12:47.750
But in this region out here,
you don't have dijets anymore.

01:12:47.750 --> 01:12:50.235
That's where tau is
starting to get large

01:12:50.235 --> 01:12:51.485
and you no longer have dijets.

01:12:57.320 --> 01:12:59.690
So if you wanted to think
about sort of higher order

01:12:59.690 --> 01:13:02.480
corrections in the
distribution out here,

01:13:02.480 --> 01:13:05.030
then you would need to
perhaps think about three jets

01:13:05.030 --> 01:13:06.230
and other things.

01:13:06.230 --> 01:13:08.480
In particular, there's
also a kind of shoulder

01:13:08.480 --> 01:13:10.260
here that if you
really want to think

01:13:10.260 --> 01:13:12.260
about how power corrections
are kind of properly

01:13:12.260 --> 01:13:17.930
dealing with that region, you
think about more than two jets.

01:13:17.930 --> 01:13:21.390
But if you just kind of restrict
yourself to here and here,

01:13:21.390 --> 01:13:25.222
which is all we're going to
do, then you don't-- then every

01:13:25.222 --> 01:13:26.930
mode, even if you go
to subleading order,

01:13:26.930 --> 01:13:28.460
is exactly the ones
that we just said.

01:13:28.460 --> 01:13:31.002
And you just have to deal with
them by constructing operators

01:13:31.002 --> 01:13:33.320
in subleading order.

01:13:33.320 --> 01:13:38.430
So that's the more detailed
answer to your question.

01:13:38.430 --> 01:13:39.852
Any other questions?

01:13:43.710 --> 01:13:50.490
OK, so I'll say a few things
about the perturbation theory.

01:13:50.490 --> 01:13:53.400
So so far we've kind
of argued that we

01:13:53.400 --> 01:13:56.610
could get pretty far without
doing perturbation theory.

01:13:56.610 --> 01:13:59.640
So we got here without
doing perturbation theory.

01:13:59.640 --> 01:14:02.670
What if we actually now want
to calculate these series,

01:14:02.670 --> 01:14:05.258
do the normalization
group evolution?

01:14:05.258 --> 01:14:06.300
How's that going to work?

01:14:10.970 --> 01:14:13.360
And it's actually--
in some ways,

01:14:13.360 --> 01:14:17.350
it's a combination of the
two examples that we treated.

01:14:17.350 --> 01:14:20.080
We did an example where we
had a Wilson coefficient that

01:14:20.080 --> 01:14:21.520
was just running
multiplicatively,

01:14:21.520 --> 01:14:22.990
and we did another
example where we

01:14:22.990 --> 01:14:25.642
had a function for deep
and elastic scattering.

01:14:25.642 --> 01:14:27.100
It had an integral,
and we're going

01:14:27.100 --> 01:14:29.620
to have both of those
situations in this case.

01:14:34.370 --> 01:14:37.030
So let me tell you how it works.

01:14:37.030 --> 01:14:41.500
So to get the hard function,
you would do some matching,

01:14:41.500 --> 01:14:44.470
and the matching is actually for
what people call the quark form

01:14:44.470 --> 01:14:46.578
factor.

01:14:46.578 --> 01:14:49.120
So if you wonder why people care
about the quark form factor,

01:14:49.120 --> 01:14:50.830
the quark form
factor is basically

01:14:50.830 --> 01:14:54.040
the h in our
formula, not exactly,

01:14:54.040 --> 01:14:56.430
but closely related to
the h in our formula.

01:15:00.470 --> 01:15:06.640
So you would do some one loop
matching by taking QCD graphs

01:15:06.640 --> 01:15:10.030
and subtracting the SCET graphs
in exactly the kind of way

01:15:10.030 --> 01:15:13.482
we were already doing
for the examples

01:15:13.482 --> 01:15:14.440
that we treated before.

01:15:24.030 --> 01:15:25.430
So those are collinear gluons.

01:15:25.430 --> 01:15:26.690
This is an ultra soft gluon.

01:15:29.650 --> 01:15:33.290
And there's some wave function
graphs that you can consider.

01:15:33.290 --> 01:15:35.180
We form the difference.

01:15:35.180 --> 01:15:38.390
And at one loop, we check
that all the IR divergences

01:15:38.390 --> 01:15:41.330
between this and this
cancel, and then we

01:15:41.330 --> 01:15:42.925
get the Wilson coefficient.

01:15:48.270 --> 01:15:51.230
So this is very, very
analogous to the example

01:15:51.230 --> 01:15:53.810
that we did when we were
doing a heavy light current.

01:16:12.180 --> 01:16:15.870
And you see here that this
thing, which depends on mu,

01:16:15.870 --> 01:16:18.060
it's mu over q.

01:16:18.060 --> 01:16:20.100
And that's what I was
saying that the Wilson

01:16:20.100 --> 01:16:22.050
coefficient or the hard
function should be--

01:16:22.050 --> 01:16:25.996
the log should be minimized
from mu of order q.

01:16:25.996 --> 01:16:27.870
And we see that by
doing the calculation.

01:16:32.910 --> 01:16:36.600
H is the square of this thing.

01:16:36.600 --> 01:16:39.390
So there's imaginary parts
on these negative logarithms.

01:16:39.390 --> 01:16:41.640
These are minus q
squared minus i 0.

01:16:41.640 --> 01:16:43.860
But when I take the mod
square, this thing is real.

01:16:50.850 --> 01:16:53.550
What about the jet function?

01:16:53.550 --> 01:16:56.280
Well, if you go back to what
the formula for the jet function

01:16:56.280 --> 01:17:00.360
was, the jet
function is basically

01:17:00.360 --> 01:17:06.090
two fields like spit out a
quark and absorb a quark.

01:17:06.090 --> 01:17:07.760
But it's a vacuum
matrix element,

01:17:07.760 --> 01:17:10.207
so the quarks are
just contracted.

01:17:10.207 --> 01:17:11.790
So you're basically
calculating graphs

01:17:11.790 --> 01:17:14.290
like this or, really, actually
the imaginary parts of graphs

01:17:14.290 --> 01:17:16.092
like this because
the way I drew it,

01:17:16.092 --> 01:17:17.550
you were summing
over final states,

01:17:17.550 --> 01:17:20.770
so it would be the
imaginary part.

01:17:20.770 --> 01:17:24.210
So we could just calculate the
graphs without putting a cut in

01:17:24.210 --> 01:17:26.430
and take the imaginary part,
and that would actually

01:17:26.430 --> 01:17:28.700
be giving us the jet function.

01:17:28.700 --> 01:17:32.760
So the jet function comes
from some Feynman diagrams

01:17:32.760 --> 01:17:33.870
that look like this.

01:17:37.980 --> 01:17:44.480
And then there's one
more looks like that.

01:17:44.480 --> 01:17:46.850
So at one move, we have
those three Feynman diagrams.

01:17:46.850 --> 01:17:48.110
And then we have the
[INAUDIBLE] little guy.

01:17:48.110 --> 01:17:49.100
We take the imaginary part.

01:17:49.100 --> 01:17:50.100
We get the jet function.

01:17:56.810 --> 01:17:58.850
At lowest order, it
gives a delta function

01:17:58.850 --> 01:18:00.020
just to cut propagator.

01:18:07.020 --> 01:18:09.390
And then at one [INAUDIBLE],,
you get a delta function,

01:18:09.390 --> 01:18:10.860
and you also get plus functions.

01:18:17.420 --> 01:18:24.640
That may not worry so much
about what the numbers are.

01:18:24.640 --> 01:18:28.015
I can just tell you what
the result looks like.

01:18:28.015 --> 01:18:29.170
It looks like that.

01:18:29.170 --> 01:18:32.028
There's three different types
of terms that we could get.

01:18:32.028 --> 01:18:33.820
They all kind of have
a power counting that

01:18:33.820 --> 01:18:35.517
makes them go like one over s.

01:18:35.517 --> 01:18:36.850
And that you know ahead of time.

01:18:36.850 --> 01:18:39.760
If you power count
the operator here,

01:18:39.760 --> 01:18:40.990
it should scale one over s.

01:18:40.990 --> 01:18:42.740
These are the different
kind of structures

01:18:42.740 --> 01:18:45.317
that you can get at one
loop that scale one over s.

01:18:45.317 --> 01:18:46.900
And this is kind of
a symptom of there

01:18:46.900 --> 01:18:49.275
being 1 over epsilon
squared divergences,

01:18:49.275 --> 01:18:50.650
and this guy here
are [INAUDIBLE]

01:18:50.650 --> 01:18:51.692
the renormalized results.

01:18:51.692 --> 01:18:55.490
So we're taking care
of the renormalization.

01:18:55.490 --> 01:18:57.380
So just like in our example--

01:18:57.380 --> 01:18:59.450
I mean, it's the
same diagram really.

01:18:59.450 --> 01:19:02.420
Just this diagram was
familiar because this diagram

01:19:02.420 --> 01:19:04.130
was showing up in
beta s gamma, right?

01:19:04.130 --> 01:19:06.800
So we saw it had 1 over
epsilon squared poles.

01:19:06.800 --> 01:19:10.862
Here, the 1 over epsilon
squared poles lead to this.

01:19:10.862 --> 01:19:12.320
And, really, you
can actually think

01:19:12.320 --> 01:19:13.820
of that very closely
related to what

01:19:13.820 --> 01:19:16.970
we did because we were finding
logs of mu squared over p

01:19:16.970 --> 01:19:20.040
squared, but here, p
squared is a physical thing.

01:19:20.040 --> 01:19:23.780
It's the s, the invariant mass
that we pump into the operator.

01:19:23.780 --> 01:19:28.810
S is kind of what we
put in through the--

01:19:28.810 --> 01:19:33.830
we put in a momentum,
if you like, q, where--

01:19:33.830 --> 01:19:34.820
I shouldn't call it q--

01:19:37.622 --> 01:19:41.990
t mu where s is
t squared, right?

01:19:41.990 --> 01:19:45.890
And so before we were having
logs of p squared, which

01:19:45.890 --> 01:19:48.740
were an IR regulator, but in
this calculation for this jet

01:19:48.740 --> 01:19:50.990
function, it's actually
a physical thing.

01:19:50.990 --> 01:19:54.840
And it's giving the momentum
dependents of the jet function,

01:19:54.840 --> 01:19:58.400
but it's the right thing to
stick into the factorization

01:19:58.400 --> 01:20:00.200
theorem.

01:20:00.200 --> 01:20:02.990
And then there's
the soft function

01:20:02.990 --> 01:20:08.180
where if it's perturbative,
you can calculate it.

01:20:08.180 --> 01:20:12.320
And you can draw these kind of
in some notation for the Wilson

01:20:12.320 --> 01:20:13.800
lines.

01:20:13.800 --> 01:20:21.680
So here's our Wilson lines
in different directions.

01:20:21.680 --> 01:20:23.970
And then want this
matrix element squared,

01:20:23.970 --> 01:20:26.060
and, again, you
can sort of think

01:20:26.060 --> 01:20:30.590
of as kind of cut graphs
like that if you like.

01:20:30.590 --> 01:20:35.540
And if we look at
the soft function,

01:20:35.540 --> 01:20:39.720
it kind of has a similar
structure to the jet function

01:20:39.720 --> 01:20:43.200
but now with the--

01:20:43.200 --> 01:20:46.730
so, again, it's got a
delta function and then

01:20:46.730 --> 01:20:47.660
plus functions.

01:20:55.541 --> 01:20:56.041
Whoops.

01:21:00.500 --> 01:21:03.830
And it turns out there's
no single plus function,

01:21:03.830 --> 01:21:09.470
but there is a plus function
with a logarithm in this case.

01:21:09.470 --> 01:21:17.920
And then same for l minus.

01:21:17.920 --> 01:21:19.480
Same structure.

01:21:19.480 --> 01:21:21.560
It's just a product if you like.

01:21:21.560 --> 01:21:24.020
And the reason that happens
is if you only have one gluon,

01:21:24.020 --> 01:21:26.030
it's either in hemisphere
A or hemisphere

01:21:26.030 --> 01:21:27.900
B. It can't be in both.

01:21:27.900 --> 01:21:30.500
So the alpha s corrections are
either a function of l plus

01:21:30.500 --> 01:21:32.540
or a function of l
minus, and that's

01:21:32.540 --> 01:21:34.860
why it has a kind of very
simple structure at one loop.

01:21:52.235 --> 01:21:53.610
So that gives you
an idea of what

01:21:53.610 --> 01:21:55.980
these perturbative
functions look like.

01:21:55.980 --> 01:21:58.380
C, if you talk about
renormalization,

01:21:58.380 --> 01:22:01.067
C renormalizes multiplicatively.

01:22:05.050 --> 01:22:08.320
And so the renormalization
group equation for C

01:22:08.320 --> 01:22:13.320
is just like the one we had
before for beta s gamma.

01:22:17.600 --> 01:22:19.100
There's no integrals.

01:22:19.100 --> 01:22:20.900
That, again, came about
from the kinematics

01:22:20.900 --> 01:22:22.970
fixing the variables.

01:22:22.970 --> 01:22:30.950
But the jet function
and the soft function

01:22:30.950 --> 01:22:34.310
have convolutions in this case.

01:22:41.232 --> 01:22:43.190
Well, they depend on this
non-trivial momentum,

01:22:43.190 --> 01:22:45.170
and it's--

01:22:45.170 --> 01:22:48.620
you can see in the factorization
theorem, that is convoluting

01:22:48.620 --> 01:22:49.880
between two different sectors.

01:22:49.880 --> 01:22:52.310
And it kind of
generically a hint

01:22:52.310 --> 01:22:57.332
that you're going to get out
a formula like this one, which

01:22:57.332 --> 01:23:01.140
is like the PDF, but now
it's a different formula.

01:23:01.140 --> 01:23:05.040
It was kind of an almost
dimension for the jet function.

01:23:09.350 --> 01:23:11.620
So we could go through
that, but I was not

01:23:11.620 --> 01:23:14.792
writing down for you what the
1 over epsilons look like.

01:23:14.792 --> 01:23:18.940
But we could go through
the renormalization

01:23:18.940 --> 01:23:20.310
and find these results.

01:23:31.520 --> 01:23:33.470
And actually, in this
jet function case,

01:23:33.470 --> 01:23:36.140
we even know more.

01:23:36.140 --> 01:23:39.680
The general structure of
this anomalous dimension

01:23:39.680 --> 01:23:42.350
is actually simpler than the
Parton distribution case.

01:23:46.370 --> 01:23:49.795
And it's the following.

01:23:56.590 --> 01:24:00.155
There's two types of
terms that can show up.

01:24:00.155 --> 01:24:02.280
So the general structure
of the anomalous dimension

01:24:02.280 --> 01:24:05.700
is that there's a
single plus function

01:24:05.700 --> 01:24:07.710
in it or a delta function.

01:24:07.710 --> 01:24:10.620
And this single plus
function is the analog

01:24:10.620 --> 01:24:13.050
